03906nam a22004935i 9780887553974DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875539747 a10.1515/97808875539742doi  a(DE-B1597)664724  a(OCoLC)1406790814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a813.541 aRiegel, Christian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting Grief :bMargaret Laurence and the Work of Mourning /cChristian Riegel. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tMourning, Work, and Liminality in the Manawaka Fiction -- tSpeaking the Heart's Truth: Hagar's Work of Mourning in the Stone Angel -- tTransgressing the Taboos: Rachel's Work of Mourning -- tThe Crisis of Word and Meaning: the Work of Mourning and the Loss of Consolation -- t"Rest Beyond the River": Mourning In a Bird in the House -- tThe Diviners and the Work of Mourning -- tLaurence and the Elegiac Tradition -- tEndnotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMargaret Laurence's much admired Manawaka fiction - The Stone Angel, A Jest of God, The Fire-Dwellers, A Bird in the House, and The Diviners – has achieved remarkable recognition for its compassionate portrayal of the attempt to find meaning and peace in ordinary life. In Writing Grief, Christian Riegel argues that the protagonists in these books achieve resolution through acts of mourning, placing this fiction within the larger tradition of writing that explores the nuances and strategies of mourning. Riegel's analysis alludes to sociological and literary antecedants of the study of mourning, including the tradition of elegy, from Derrida and Lacan to Freud, van Gennep, and Milton. The "work" of mourning is necessary to move from a state of emotional paralysis to one of acceptance and active engagement. Laurence's characters "perform the work of mourning . returning over and over again to the key issues relating to loss," and, as Riegel's close examination of the texts suggests, are changed thereafter fundamentally and significantly. As an important study of one aspect of Laurence's oeuvre, Writing Grief not only illustrates how Laurence's own preoccupations with mourning are figured, but also how different ways of working through grief result in renewed potential for consolation and connection, and "a renewed definition of self."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755397440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553974423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553974/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles